@node Distribution

Netris is FreeWare.  Distribute it wherever you wish, but keep
all files from the archive together.  Money, candy, flowers, and
nubile young slave girls will all be gratefully accepted, but are 
not required or requested.  If you want the source code, email me 
and I will send it to you.  You are required, however, to report 
any bugs so that I can squash them ASAP.  :)

@endnode

@node KnownProblems

- Too much Netris traffic can overload AmiTCP, causing it to run
  out of buffer space, panic, and need to be restarted.  (This
  may be a bug in AmiTCP, though)

- Apparently Netris sometimes "forgets" and resets its high score 
  table when a competitor exits ungracefully (e.g. by rebooting).
  
- There in an occasional Enforcer hit on exit.

- Netris very occasionally crashes my machine.  It happens rarely
  enough and so seemingly at random that I haven't been able to
  track down what is causing it!
  
@endnode

@node History

1.14  : (Public Release 10/6/97)
 - Made the high score chart display a little prettier (it now
   says "Game Over" in angry red letters)
 * Added checksums to the high score tables, to avoid spreading
   corrupt data.  Note that this means that Netris v1.14 and above
   will ignore high scores that were created by Netris clients
   v1.13 and below (because earlier Netris versions do not generate 
   checksums).
 
1.13  : (Public Release 10/12/97)
 - Modified the scoring system so that each score addition is multiplied
   by the number of people playing.  This should keep the high-score lists
   from being monopolized by "easy" single-player games.
 - Netris can now bind macros to the function keys (F1-F10).  See the
   @{"MACRO ToolTypes" link ToolTypes} section for more info.
 - The Delete and Help keys now rotate the dropping piece left and right,
   respectively (and may be redefined to other uses--see below).
 - Made the piece control key bindings customizable.  See the @{"KEY ToolTypes" link ToolTypes}
   section for more info.  (Note that the SMALLDROP ToolType is obsolete!  
   Use the customizable key binding ToolTypes to achieve the same effect.)
 - Made the default server for Netris be qamitrack.tibb.at.  (The
   proprieter thinks his computer can handle this--we will see if it can! ;))
 - Made the default user name be "Netris Newbie".  This will encourage
   people to enter a better name quickly, I think.  :)
 - Added more (commented out) example ToolTypes to the Netris icon.
 * Game state info is now allocated on the heap, instead of on the stack.
   This should keep Netris from using too much stack space.
    
1.12  : (Public Release 7/7/97)
 - Added the SMALLDROP @{"ToolType" link ToolTypes} for people who don't
   like to drop their tile all the way to the bottom at once.
 * Netris is now compiled with the -ffp option, so that it no longer will
   crash 68060 systems.
   
1.11B : (Beta Release 6/15/97)
 - Added the TILEPEN(0-6) and PENCOLOR(0-7) @{"ToolType" link ToolTypes} arrays.
 * Reduced (but didn't eliminate) the drops-tiles-at-super-speed-
   if-you-restart-your-game-too-quickly-after-dying bug.
 * Netris wasn't calling QFreeSession() when it quit!
   This caused the TCP Client thread, and thus the TCP connection 
   to the AMarquee server, to hang around indefinitely afterwards.
   Very bad.  :(
 * The high score displays can no longer write outside the bounding
   box of the game they are displayed in.
   
1.10B : (Beta Release 6/10/97)
NOTE: V1.10B is not compatible with v1.00B.  The two versions may both
      be logged into the same AMarquee server at the same time, and they
      won't interfere with one another, but they won't interact, either.
 - Rewrote the chat lines to work in line-mode rather than character
   mode.  This allows for more space to read in.  Added the SOUND7
   ToolType and chatline.8svx soundfile to be played when a chat line
   is transmitted.
 - Added the NAME, WORKBENCH, and DISPLAYID ToolTypes.
 - Added high-score tables (and the HIGHSCOREFILE ToolType).
 - Added a packet throttle that stops sending TileMoved packets whenever
   the network becomes congested.  (Note: to support this feature, 
   amarquee.library v44 is now required)
 - Changed the color scheme for the various tiles.
 - Tile shadow is now the same color as the falling tile.
 * If a player's connection is broken during his game, his game will
   not be left active on the other computers' screens anymore.
 * Now honors the PORT ToolType.
 * Now looks for the default sound effects in PROGDIR: rather than
   the current working directory.
 * Sound effect distribution was broken.
 
1.00B : (Beta Release 5/25/97)
 - First release.  

@endnode

@node Requirements

To use Netris, you will need the following:

 - An Amiga with some free memory
 - Workbench 2.04 or greater
 - An Internet connection (if you want to play against other people)
 - AmiTCP (or a compatible TCP stack) set up and running.
 - @{"amarquee.library" link amarquee.library} v44+ in your LIBS: directory.
 
@endnode

@node Credits

Netris was written by me, Jeremy Friesner (jfriesne@ucsd.edu)

Compiled with DICE C by Matt Dillon

Most of the included sound effects were blatantly stolen from 
several archives on Aminet, notably the Term sound effects archives.  
(The exception is startgame.8svx, which I sampled from a They
Might Be Giants CD)

@endnode

@node Introduction

Netris is a four player, Internet version of the old classic,
Tetris.  It uses the AMarquee system to allow you to play against
up to three people (each on their own Amiga) at once.  In addition
to this, any number of "viewers" may watch the games currently in 
progress (limited only by the server's bandwidth and CPU).

Note that Netris requires @{"amarquee.library" link amarquee.library} v44+ to be installed
in your LIBS: directory.  If you don't have this library, download
the archive /comm/net/AMarquee1.44.lha from Aminet and install it.

To play Netris by yourself, you can just run it and then choose
which board to play on, by pressing a function key between F1 and F4.  
But playing by yourself is boring; there are dozens of Tetris games
on Aminet that let you do that!  What you want to do is play
against other people.  To do this, you need an AMarquee server--
that is, an Amiga with the AMarqueed daemon installed and available.
The AMarquee server can be one of the Tetris-players' computers,
or another computer, it doesn't matter.  But it is preferable
that the AMarquee server have plenty of RAM, CPU, and network
bandwidth to the client computers, as all game data will pass
through it during play.  The AMarqueed daemon is also available
in the AMarquee1.44.lha archive, as described above.

Once the AMarquee server is setup and available, each player
should edit the ToolTypes of their Netris icon and set the
SERVER ToolType to the name of the server computer.  After
that, it's just a matter of running Netris--it should connect
to the server, and be ready to play against other people.

The following files should be in the Netris archive:

