@node Installation

Just copy the executable file and icon to wherever you want 
to keep them.  Also, make sure the included .8svx sound files are
kept in the same directory as the Netris executable, so that 
Netris can find them.

Make sure that @{"amarquee.library" link amarquee.library} v44+ is installed
in your LIBS: directory!

If you wish to use your computer as an AMarquee server to host
Netris games, you will need to install AMarqueed onto your system
as well.  The AMarqueed program is also available in the AMarquee1.44.lha
archive on Aminet.

@endnode


@node ToolTypes

Netris understands the following parameters.  These parameters
may be set either as ToolTypes in Netris's icon, or specified
on the command line (in the same exact format as the tooltypes,
although you may have to use "quote marks" if the parameter 
contains spaces):

SERVER/K:
    Specifies the IP name of the server Amiga that Netris should 
    connect to.  If this isn't specified, Netris will report an
    error, and only single-player play will be available.
    
PORT/K/N:
    Specifies the port number that Netris should try to connect to when
    initiating a connection to the server Amiga.  The default (and
    usual) value for this parameter is 2957.

NODOWNLOAD/S:
    If specified, Netris will not download any sound effects from
    the other Netris clients.
    
NOUPLOAD/S:
    If specified, Netris will not upload any sound effects to the
    other Netris clients.

NAME/K:
    Allows you to specify a name yourself.  This name will appear
    in the topmost text field during your games, and in the high
    score charts whenever you get a high score.

HIGHSCOREFILE/K:
    Allows you to specify a filename to load and save high scores
    to and from.  High scores will be loaded from this file on
    startup, if it exists, and saved whenever you quit Netris.
    If this ToolType is not specified, then high scores will not
    be loaded or saved.
        
WORKBENCH/S:
    Specify the switch to run Netris in a window on the Workbench
    screen, rather than on its own custom screeen.  Note that in
    order to do this, you will need a fairly large Workbench screen
    (640x450 or larger)
    
DISPLAYID/K/N:
    If you don't like NTSC-Hires-Interlace, you can use this switch
    to force the Netris screen into another screenmode.  The value
    for this argument should be a hexadecimal screen mode ID, as
    specified in the system include file <graphics/displayinfo.h>
    
MAXDOWNLOADSIZE/K/N:
    Specifies the maximum length of sound sample that Netris will 
    download.  Samples greater than this length will be truncated
    to this length.  The default value for this is 64 (meaning
    samples greater than 64 Kilobytes in length will be truncated).
    
NOSOUND/S:
    If specified, Netris will not allocate the sound hardware,
    download, or play any sounds.  Sounds can still be uploaded,
    however.
    
SOUND0/K
SOUND1/K
...
SOUND6/K
    These ToolTypes allow you to specify your own custom sounds
    to use with Netris.  The neat part here is that not only will
    you hear your custom sound files, but anyone you play against
    will hear your sound effects as well!  Since every client will
    need to download and store your sound effects in memory, and 
    the server Amiga will keep a copy in memory as well, it is 
    best to keep your sound effects files as small as possible.  
    The maximum sample size you can use is 64K (larger samples 
    will be truncated).  All sounds should be in standard IFF-8SVX 
    format.  The SOUND ToolTypes correspond to the following game 
    occurences:
    
     SOUND0 = Played when your game starts.
     SOUND1 = Played when your game ends.
     SOUND2 = Played when you place a tile.
     SOUND3 = Played when you clear one rows of tiles.
     SOUND4 = Played when you clear two rows of tiles.
     SOUND5 = Played when you clear three rows of tiles.
     SOUND6 = Played when you clear four rows of tiles.
     SOUND7 = Played when a chat line is sent/received.
     
    Note that you could also customize the sound effects in the
    game by copying over the included .8svx default sound files;
    but unless you actually specify the SOUND* ToolTypes, the
    sounds will not be uploaded to the other players (as Netris
    will think they are default sounds, and figure that the other
    players already have them)

TILEPEN0/K/N
TILEPEN1/K/N
...
TILEPEN6/K/N
    These ToolTypes allow you to customize which pens will be
    used to draw each piece in Netris.  The default mapping is
    this:
    
      TILEPEN0=4  (backwards 'L' tile)
      TILEPEN1=5  (forwards 'L' tile)
      TILEPEN2=3  (straight tile)
      TILEPEN3=7  (square tile)
      TILEPEN4=6  ('T' tile)
      TILEPEN5=2  (chair tile)
      TILEPEN6=1  (backwards chair tile)

PENCOLOR0/K/N
PENCOLOR1/K/N
...
PENCOLOR7/K/N
    These ToolTypes allow you to specify, in RGB hexadecimal notation,
    what the color of each screen pen should be.  These ToolTypes will
    not have any effect if the WORKBENCH switch is specified (as Netris
    will not modify the pen colors of the Workbench screen).  The
    default mapping is this:
    
      PENCOLOR0 = 0x999
      PENCOLOR1 = 0x000
      PENCOLOR2 = 0xFFF
      PENCOLOR3 = 0x00F
      PENCOLOR4 = 0x0F0
      PENCOLOR5 = 0xF00
      PENCOLOR6 = 0xFF0
      PENCOLOR7 = 0xF0F

MACRO1/K
MACRO2/K
...
MACRO10/K
    These ToolTypes allow you to specify macros that will be "typed"
    for you when the corresponding function key is pressed.  These
    macros may be up to 255 characters long, and may contain the
    following escape sequences:
     
      \n  = carriage return
      \t  = tab
      \b  = backspace
      \\  = backslash char
      
    So, for example, you could set the following ToolType:
    
      MACRO6=Taste the kiss o' me steely Tetris block, knave!\n
      
    and have the computer type (and send, due to the \n) the indicated 
    text for you whenever you pressed F6.  Note that keys F1 through
    F4 are also used to start a new Tetris game, so you may want to
    use those macros only for beginning-of-game messages.

KEY_LEFT/K
KEY_RIGHT/K
KEY_UP/K
KEY_DOWN/K
KEY_HELP/K
KEY_DELETE/K
    These ToolTypes allow you to specify custom actions to be taken
    whenever one of the piece-control keys is pressed.  The keys that
    may be used for piece control are the arrow keys (left, right, up,
    and down), and also the HELP and DELETE keys.
    
    The argument to these ToolTypes is a one or two word phrase that
    indicates what should happen when the key is pressed.  The following
    phrases are understood:
    
      move left             : move the current tile left one square
      move right            : move the current tile right one square
      move down             : move the current tile down one square
      turn counterclockwise : turn the current tile 90 degrees clockwise
      turn clockwise        : turn the current tile 90 degrees counterclockwise
      drop                  : drop the current tile to the bottom
      
    The "default" key mapping (which will be used unless overridden
    by explicit KEY_* ToolTypes) is:
    
      KEY_LEFT=move left
      KEY_RIGHT=move right
      KEY_UP=turn clockwise
      KEY_DOWN=drop
      KEY_DELETE=turn counterclockwise
      KEY_HELP=turn clockwise
      
    Finally, you may use the word "translate" as a synonym for "move",
    "rotate" as a synonym for "turn", and "left" or "right" as a synonym
    for "counterclockwise" or "clockwise", respectively.

@endnode

@node Using
 
Using Netris is fairly simple.  Once you are connected (see
@{"Introduction" link Introduction} for information on how to connect Netris to a server),
you simply choose one of the four Netris play areas to play in,
by pressing a number key between '1' and '4'.  A blue square should
appear around the appropriate play area, and your game should begin.
Note that you cannot start a game in play areas that already have
a game active in them--so if all four game areas are active, you
will have to wait for one of the games to end, or find another Netris
server!

Once the game is started, use the arrow keys to maneuver your tile.
Left and right move the tile left and right, Up rotates it ninety
degrees, and down moves it to the bottom of the play area.
(Note that you can redefine the actions taken when these keys are
pressed:  see ToolTypes, under @{"KEY_*" link ToolTypes}, for more info)

If you don't know the rules of Tetris... then you should be ashamed
of yourself.  It's 1997!  Where have you been?  ;)  Well, you'll 
probably figure them out soon enough.  One note, however--if you 
clear more than one row of tiles at once, your opponents will get 
(# of rows cleared - 1) rows of garbage tiles added to their boards.  
That should piss 'em off.  ;)

Also, you may use the other keys on the keyboard at any time to type 
messages to the other players.  Your message will be entered into
the line at the bottom of the screen, and broadcast to all other 
clients when you press return.  The message will have a block of
color next to it to denote which game (if any) it was sent from.

Scoring is simple:  For every tile you place, 

  (# of rows cleared)
(3                   )*(number of players currently playing)

points is added to your score.  High score tables are kept by each
client, and each client will broadcast its high score table to all
other clients on its server.  Thus, high scores tables will be merged
whenever possible.

Finally, you may press Escape at any time to end your game, or to
quit Netris.

@endnode

